title: TIGER/Line Shapefile, 2015, Series Information for the Feature Names County-based Relationship File
name: tiger-line-shapefile-2015-series-information-for-the-feature-names-county-based-relationship-fi
notes: The MTDB represents a seamless national file with no overlaps or gaps between parts, however, each TIGER/Line File is designed to stand alone as ann               independent data set, or they can be combined to cover the entire nation.  The Feature Names Relationship File (FEATNAMES.dbf) contains a record for eachn               feature name and any attributes associated with it.  Each feature name can be linked to the corresponding edges that make up that feature in the Alln               Lines Shapefile (EDGES.shp), where applicable to the corresponding address range or ranges in the Address Ranges Relationship File (ADDR.dbf), or to bothn               files.  Although this file includes feature names for all linear features, not just road features, the primary purpose of this relationship file is ton               identify all street names associated with each address range.  An edge can have several feature names; an address range located on an edge can ben               associated with one or any combination of the available feature names (an address range can be linked to multiple feature names).  The address range isn               identified by the address range identifier (ARID) attribute, which can be used to link to the Address Ranges Relationship File (ADDR.dbf).  The linearn               feature is identified by the linear feature identifier (LINEARID) attribute,  which can be used to relate the address range back to the name attributesn               of the feature in the Feature Names Relationship File or to the feature record in the Primary Roads, Primary and Secondary Roads, or All Roadsn               Shapefiles. The edge to which a feature name applies can be determined by linking the feature name record to the All Lines Shapefile (EDGES.shp) usingn               the permanent edge identifier (TLID) attribute.  The address range identifier(s) (ARID) for a specific linear feature can be found by using the linearn               feature identifier (LINEARID) from the Feature Names Relationship File (FEATNAMES.dbf) through the Address Range / Feature Name Relationship Filen               (ADDRFN.dbf). n               n               The TIGER/Line shapefiles and related database files (.dbf) are an extract of selected geographic and cartographic information from then               U.S. Census Bureau's Master Address File / Topologically Integrated Geographic Encoding and Referencing (MAF/TIGER) Database (MTDB).  The MTDB representsn               a seamless national file with no overlaps or gaps between parts, however, each TIGER/Line shapefile is designed to stand alone as an independent datan               set, or they can be combined to cover the entire nation.
